<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Aaric on 05-22-2002 12:56 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Multi-boxing can be a curse or a boon, depending on how much time you spend doing it.

For instance, the single most important thing is to set up properly.  Get all your spells hotkeyed, and make sure your group listings are the same on both computers.  (so F2 will target your other toon, and F3-F6 target the same people on both machines)  Another good idea is to have your important spells in the bottom 4 slots hotkeyed 1-4, and use Alt-1 to alt-4 for the other spells.  That way, you can cast any of your 8 spells using one hand on the left side of the keyboard.  The physical setup of your computers needs optimized so you can see the other monitor(s) and the KB/mouse are easily accessable.

I played my cleric solo to 60 and had about 150 days on him.  When they added macros, my cleric playing experience was incredibly boring.  Granted clericing isn't all about sitting and healing, but in most situations, that's all that is required.  So much about being a cleric is knowing whats going on and whats going to happen...and I find multi-boxing actually gives me a better view of the entire situation.  Additionally, playing cleric/chanter in the same group lets you manage mana by slowing/rooting very efficiently.

I leveled my rogue to 60 on another account, and am currently bringing my enchanter (2 yellows to 60 - whee!) up on a 3rd box.  I routinely raid with my rogue/cleric (NToV, Deep, Ssra, etc) and routinely 3 box for xp.  I ended up 3 boxing at a raid recently spot healing/runing the MT, and doing crowd control of adds.

Granted, I will drop to a single box if its a new area, or I am having to coordinate a heal rotation, run groups, or am not up to the attention required.

For instance, last night I was in the hole
with my 'partner' who was running a 54 druid and a 56 monk, and we managed to derail a 10 mob 'pull' which included 7 golems.  Most pickup groups you would see would get pummeled by a pull half that size.

Calling all multi-boxers bad, is like saying all druids are soling farmers.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
